 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
a. OBRA 89 Provisions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
&bull;Rural primary care hospitals. A new category of provider, rural primary care hospitals, was established (section
6003(g)(3) of OBRA 89). Only facilities currently certified as hospitals and not in violation of any conditions of
participation (42 CFR part 482) could be designated by the Secretary as rural primary care hospitals. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Compliance requirements (section 6018 of OBRA 89). Hospitals are required to_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Adopt and enforce a policy to ensure compliance with section 1867 of the Act; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Maintain medical and other records related to individuals transferred to or from a hospital for a period
of 5 years from the transfer date; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Maintain a list of on-call physicians available for duty to provide treatment needed to stabilize an individual
with an emergency medical condition. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Posted information (section 6018 of OBRA 89). Participating hospitals must post conspicuously in their emergency
departments_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
 +&blank;A sign listing the rights of individuals under section 1867 of the Act regarding examination and treatment
for emergency medical conditions; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Information indicating whether the facility participates in the Medicaid program under a State plan approved
under title XIX of the Act. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Both posted items are to be in a form specified by the Secretary. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Additional requirements for Medicare participating hospitals with emergency departments (section 6211
of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
OBRA 89). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;The medical screening requirement was changed to indicate that the capability of the facility's emergency
department includes ``ancillary services routinely available to the emergency department.'' 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Participating facilities are now required to inform each individual (or a person acting on his or her behalf)
of the risks and benefits to the individual of examination and treatment and/or transfer, and to ``take all reasonable
steps to secure the individual's (or person's) written informed consent to refuse such examination and treatment''
and/or transfer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Changes were made relating to the restrictions on transfers to include_
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 02 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=15 g=1 f=1 -->
_A requirement that participating facilities obtain written requests for transfer to another medical facility
after informing individuals (or legally responsible persons acting on their behalf) of the hospital's obligations
and the risk of transfer; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_An explicit statement that there should be consideration of the risks and benefits to unborn children of women in
labor in determining whether the physician should certify that the benefits outweigh the risks of transfer; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_A requirement that transfer certifications by participating facilities include a summary of the risks and benefits
upon which the certification is based; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_A requirement that when a qualified medical person signs the certification, it be done in consultation with a physician
and that the physician later countersign the certification; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_A requirement that the hospital provide medical treatment within its capacity to minimize the risks of transfer;
and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_A requirement that the transferring hospital include specified documents in the medical records sent to receiving
hospitals.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 02 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
&bull;Civil monetary penalties (section 6211(e) of OBRA 89). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
+&blank;Physicians, including on-call physicians, are subject to civil monetary penalties and exclusion from
Medicare and the State health care programs for violations of section 1867 of the Act, including_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=15 g=1 f=1 -->
_The signing of transfer certifications if the physician knew or should have known that the benefits of transfer did
not outweigh the risks; or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
_Misrepresenting an individual's condition or other information on the transfer certification.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG QTAG 02 -->
<!-- PJG /QTAG -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
+&blank;A participating facility or an on-call physician is subject to a penalty if the on-call physician fails or
refuses to appear within a reasonable period of time when notified by an emergency department physician that his or
her services are needed and the emergency physician orders a transfer because he or she determines that without the
services of the on-call physician the benefits of transfer outweigh the risks of transfer. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;Specialty hospitals (section 6211(f) of OBRA 89). Participating hospitals with special capabilities or
facilities are obligated to accept the appropriate transfer of an individual who requires such specialized capabilities
or facilities if the hospital has the capacity to treat the individual. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
&bull;No delay in examination or treatment (section 6211(f) of OBRA 89). Participating hospitals are not to delay
the provision of a medical screening examination, treatment, or both, to inquire about the individual's method of
payment or insurance status. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

